post_text:
*Million Dollar Scholarship Endowment Announcement*

Green County Schools today announced a $1 million scholarship endowment in memory of Morris and Leona Ingram, former educators in Green County and Jefferson County. The Ingram’s were lifelong educators and wanted to provide a path for future educators residing in their birthplace, Green County.

The endowment, known as “The Morris and Leona Ingram Memorial Scholarship for Future Educators”, will be used to help cover tuition for first generation college students who intend to enter the field of Education as a teacher while attending a Kentucky college or university. Established with $1 million bequeathed by Morris and Leona Ingram, the scholarship will be offered to eligible graduating seniors of Green County High School.

#GCSchools #WeCARE

post_text:
Green County Schools will continue to utilize non-traditional instruction September 8 - September 11. There will be no assignments on Monday, September 7 as this is Labor Day.

Although our Active Case Index will show a slight decrease today, we are not in a position to resume in-person classes next week. Let’s continue to wear a mask, wash our hands, and social distance. As previously mentioned, this will be reviewed weekly. Pending a decrease in our index, Green County Schools will now look at Monday, September 14 as a possible return date to in-person classes. We look forward to a return to the in-person option once our community cases stabilize.

We appreciate the patience of our community and dedication of our staff during this time!

Have a great Labor Day weekend!

post_text:
This afternoon our community will see a decrease in our Active Case Index. While we hope for the continual release of active cases, part of this decrease is a result of a baseline adjustment at the close of August. The district continually evaluates the index through a review of historical data. We want our index to depict an accurate picture of the virus activity in our community.

Over the next several days, we hope to see cases released. Let’s continue to do our part in reducing new active cases by wearing a mask, practicing social distancing, and practicing hand hygiene.

Mr. Hodges explains a bit more about the baseline index and his desire to see students return for in-seat instruction in the following video:

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1HM1egu-WmYpT5NF3neXosfOn85U4ulR_/view?usp=sharing

post_text:
September 1, 2020

Dear Students, Parents/Guardians, Staff, and Community Members of Green County Schools:

Green County Schools received official notice today that two employees of the district received a positive diagnosis for COVID-19. The employees that tested positive work for the Transportation Department and last worked within the district on Wednesday, August 26. These individuals adhered to mitigation procedures that have been published in our reopening plan. If there are individuals that have been in direct contact (closer than 6 feet) with these employees for longer than ten minutes, they will be contacted by our local health department in regards to quarantining procedures. Please help us as we keep these employees in our thoughts and prayers.

The district will continue to remain transparent with our community and we will continue to take necessary precautions in order to maintain the health and safety of our students, their families, and our staff.

Thank you for your patience and support during this trying time!

Sincerely,

William L. Hodges
Superintendent

We will add a note of commentary that usually there is substantial testing conducted on Mondays and those results are usually reported on Tuesdays and Wednesdays. Hopefully this week's testing will show that our community is healing.

Let's continue to be mindful that COVID-19 is within our community. Wash your hands. Social distance. Wear a face covering.

Happy Monday!

Today is the first day of virtual learning for many of our students.

Some of you are already pros at this, but for those of you that are new, we are here to help if you need it! We encourage you to ask questions of your teachers. Teachers will hold daily office hours. Any questions asked outside of those office hours will be answered within 24-hours.

You may also call our schools and they should be able to connect you with someone to provide assistance.
Green County Primary School: 270-932-6619
Green County Intermediate School: 270-932-6613
Green County Middle School: 270-932-6615

Green County Schools is saddened to announce the passing of longtime Green County Schools Superintendent, Mr. Marshall “Buddy” Lowe. In addition to his service in the school system, Mr. Lowe was well-known throughout our community and beyond for his dedication to many civic, artistic, and religious organizations. Our community is a better place because of Mr. Lowe’s selfless actions throughout his entire life.

Our thoughts and prayers are with his loved ones and friends during this difficult time.

We have been dedicated to open and transparent communication since the COVID-19 pandemic started in March.

Earlier today we reported a potential positive from a Green County High School employee. After an investigation by our public health partner, the Lake Cumberland District Health Department, we are pleased to report that NO STUDENTS will be quarantined as a result of this positive case.

Our mitigation procedures within our reopening plan are working. After a full week of in-seat classes we are aware of NO student positives and NO student quarantines.

We are doing our part to keep our students safe. Thank you for your trust and support!

We would like to take this opportunity to explain a little bit more about the Active Case Index and what it represents.

The Active Case Index looks at active cases in the community. This is not solely reflective of active cases within the schools itself, but for our community as a whole. Currently there are no positive student or employee cases that are included within the index.

Currently, every single case (100%) is from the community.

Our mitigation processes are working. We are transitioning to virtual learning out of an abundance of caution as community cases rise. We plan to resume in-person instruction on September 8 if our Active Case Index has returned to the "yellow phase" levels.

#GCSchools #WeCARE

Today our community Active Case Index has reached 7.98. We have had a great week in our school system and are unaware of any student cases, but the increase in community cases has caused us to reach our threshold for transitioning into the "red phase" of our reopening plan.

Mr. Hodges has released a statement regarding this transition along with a possible positive test of an employee. Additional guidance and communications will be released in the days ahead.

If you have any questions or concerns, we encourage you to reach out to any of the following individuals at Green County Schools Central Office.

Crystal Hedgespeth - HealthyAtWork Officer
Will Hodges - Superintendent
Zachary Leftwich - Director of Finance

All three can be reached at 270-932-6601.

The district will continue to remain transparent with our community and we will continue to take necessary precautions in order to maintain the health and safety of our students, their families, and our staff. Thank you for your patience and support during this trying time!

By the end of next week (August 26th) our Green County Farm Bureau parking lot will have free WI FI for all those without Internet service needing it for schoolwork.Our great organization-Kentucky Farm Bureau is “Big on Commitment to our community and Big on Education “ and is offering this at NO cost to anyone who needs it for their children’s schoolwork. Have we mentioned how much we love our custodians? Without their superb skills it would be IMPOSSIBLE for us to reopen our school buildings!

Tonight's custodial highlight takes us over to Green County Middle School! The custodial crew has every surface sanitized and sparkling clean in preparation for school tomorrow!

Our enhanced daily cleaning efforts include:
- Frequently wiping high-contact surfaces such as door knobs, counters, and student work stations.
- Refreshing bathrooms multiple times throughout the day
- Using hospital-grade cleaners on all hard surfaces
- Using electrostatic disinfectant sprayers in all classrooms

post_text:
Student safety is more than just a statement. For Green County Schools, it’s a priority!

We absolutely CARE about the health and safety of every single child in our district! During the day we follow strict social-distancing, face-covering, and hand-hygiene practices.

Just ask first-grader Conleigh about her day, “Turns out, we used hand sanitizer 30-hundred times.”

A special thanks to our outstanding custodial crews for all that they do to protect our students. We have implemented enhanced cleaning practices while students are in the buildings during the day. Then every afternoon all school buildings are deep-cleaned and thoroughly sanitized.

Today was fabulous! Let’s do it again tomorrow!

#GCSchools #WeCARE

shared_text:
Green County Primary School
August 15 at 7:15 PM ·

For Virtual Learners: each teacher will provide you with her "office hours." They will be able to discuss questions/concerns regarding the google classroom assignments during their planning time and possibly some times throughout the day as they are available to do so. We understand that many of you work and will be unable to work with your child until after normal school hours. Please understand that your teacher may not be able to get back to your question until the next day. They will not be expected to answer questions after those "office hours, " but will answer any questions by the end of the next school day. It is essential that you complete all of your assignments everyday. This is the way your child will be counted present for each day. If assignments are not completed each day, your child will be considered absent for that day. We greatly appreciate your cooperation and understanding during these times.

Another great visit!

Superintendent Hodges is making the rounds this morning wearing his #DragonPride mask! Throughout this whole pandemic we made every effort to be open and transparent in our messages to our students, families, and community.

We CARE and are concerned about ALL students…
We CARE about the students that public education is their only path.
We CARE about the student and families that may be in need of food.
We CARE about the students that may be in abusive situations.
We CARE about the physical health of each student and family.
We CARE about the socioemotional well being of each child.

We CARE about ALL staff members.

We appreciate the public's support throughout this trying time. We are looking forward to a safe and exciting return to classes on Monday.

#GCSchools #WeCARE

We CARE and are concerned about ALL students…
We CARE about the students that public education is their only path.
We CARE about the student and families that may be in need of food.
We CARE about the students that may be in abusive situations.
We CARE about the physical health of each student and family.
We CARE about the socioemotional well being of each child.

We CARE about ALL staff members.

We appreciate the public's support throughout this trying time. We are looking forward to a safe and exciting return to classes on Monday.

#GCSchools #WeCARE

Larry Joe Smith is at 99.9 The Big Dawg WVLC.
August 14 at 7:41 AM · Campbellsville, KY ·

Green County Superintendant Will Hodges talks about the start of school on Monday August 17.

We are so excited to welcome our students back Monday! We absolutely cannot wait to see them! We've been waiting since March!! There has been a change in our original plans for the first two days of school. We will no longer be able to have parents of first and second grade students in the building. Please understand that this is for the safety of your child as well as the other students, faculty and staff of GCPS. If you are bringing your child to school, please be prepared to drive through the drop off line and drop them off. There will be plenty of staff members to assist your child in getting them to their classroom. Kindergarten parents, you will be getting a message from your child's teacher to arrange a time for you to bring your child to school. Thank you for your patience and understanding as we travel down this uncharted journey.

We are very thankful for our community partners like Forcht Bank that invest so heavily in our school system and students!

post_text:
The Annual WHAS Crusade for Children Collection Efforts Are Underway!

Last year, Green County Schools received over $23,000 in crusade grants! We need YOUR help to continue receiving those grants! COVID-19 means that door-to-door collections will not be possible, but the good news is that giving to the Crusade has never been easier!

Bring your donation to the Green County Schools Central Office or drop it by any Green County fire department!

You can also give virtually in a variety of easy ways:

• Donate online at www.whascrusade.org. Be sure to list our fire dept. to receive credit!
• Text CRUSADE to 50155 to give securely via your cell phone. You will have the option to credit our fire dept.
• Venmo a donation @CrusadeForChildren and list our fire dept. in the comment section.
• CashApp a donation $CrusadeChildren and list our fire dept. in the note section.

Thank you for making WHAS Crusade for Children such a success every single year!

Parents and Guardians:

We will hold Open House on August 3rd 12:00-7:00. Whether you plan on your child attending In-Person or Virtually we would like for you to attend Open House. We will go over pertinent school information as well as google classroom access and navigation for students.
You will need to contact your child's homeroom teacher to make an appointment. Only 3 students per 45 minute session by appointment only. Each child may bring 2 adults with them during their session.
Masks are required to attend Open House. Sign-in and temperature checks will be at the front entrance of GCIS.

***If you are choosing the Virtual option please come by GCIS office between 8:00-2:30 Monday-Friday as soon as possible to complete the virtual contract.

We look forward to seeing you soon!!!

*IMPORTANT INFORMATION*

The 2020-2021 School Year is upon us and it is time to start registering your student(s). You can access the student registration website by clicking on the link below. We hope the changes that have been made this summer will make this process even better for you all.

To complete the registration for middle school and high school students attending the ATC, you will need to click on the “ATC” tab. After you review, please click the link to the "GCATC Digital Signature Sheet" and complete the form (One form per student). For questions, contact Mr. Turner at (270) 932-6605.

Mr. Hodges stopped-by the radio stations this morning to provide an update on the Green County School District's Reopening Plan for this fall. Throughout this pandemic and the district's response, including planning for the fall, we have strived to be transparent through continual communication with our students, families, and community.

Our goal has always been to maximize learning in a safe environment and our plan is designed to ensure that is possible!

In the coming days we will be utilizing a variety of methods to release our plan and keep families informed including:
- A comprehensive article in today's Greensburg Record-Herald
- Discussion on local radio stations
- Detailed video will be released on the district's social media pages
- Informational flyer will be mailed to the home of each student

#GCSchools #WeCARE

post_text:
Everyone has a story… this is ours!

We take great pride in the quality of services we can provide for the children and youth in our community. At every level of development, from Pre-Schoolers spending their first days in a school building to our graduating seniors that have been prepared for the major life transitions ahead, we provide higher-level learning while also enriching academic achievement with a great variety of co—curricular and extra-curricular opportunities.

The guide linked below provides a listing of opportunities available at each of our five schools including:
- Green County Primary School (Pre-K to 2nd Grade)
- Green County Intermediate School (3rd Grade – 5th Grade)
- Green County Middle School (6th Grade – 8th Grade)
- Green County High School (9th Grade – 12th Grade)
- Green County Area Technology Center (8th Grade – 12th Grade)

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1iOjEVOtWQBv_WhXf7F18UbwEPCFgFwe_/view?usp=sharing

#GCSchools #WeCARE

post_text:
Join us for tonight’s BOE meeting. You may need to turn the volume up on your device to hear more clearly. Unfortunately, the board room does not have the best acoustics and in order to ensure all board members are in the viewing pane (especially while members are social distancing) our device must be located in the corner of the room.

When the board goes into executive session, the live feed will be momentarily stopped. A new feed will start when the board exits executive session and resumes public business. No action may be taken during executive session.

Plan new homes and businesses and improve neighborhoods.
💚
Determine how many seats your state is allocated in the House of Representatives.

post_text:
Governor Andy Beshear has recommended that schools should not meet in person for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. Based upon that recommendation, Green County Schools will finish the school year utilizing non-traditional instruction.

Students will complete the school year on May 12 once the required number of instructional hours have been obtained.

Families will be allowed to schedule a visit to schools to pick-up personal belongings while practicing safe social distancing (additional details will be provided by each school).

Meals will be delivered to students through the month of May with the last delivery taking place on May 27.

Senior activities are currently being planned and will be released when available.

Thanks for your continued support through this difficult time.

#GCSchools #WeCARE #WeMissYou

The Green County Board of Education will hold a special-called meeting on Thursday, April 16, 2020 at 5:30 p.m. at the Board of Education. The stream will also be accessible through the district webpage, the link is https://gcsdistrict.blogspot.com/.

The full agenda can be found in the pictures attached to this post. If you have any questions, please call 270-932-6601.

Thank you!

post_text:
💚💚 What. An. Awesome. Day! 💚💚

Thanks to our community partners, today Green County Schools was able to deliver 1,934 meals to students AND around 300 food boxes with groceries to assist families over Spring Break. We can’t stress this enough... without these meals, many of our kids would be hungry and without nutritious food!

This was a MONUMENTAL task that could not have happened without our faculty, our staff, and the support of this community! This is not in their job description, but all of our employees have continually and willingly helped us meet the needs of our students during this challenging time.

We love Green County. We love our faculty and staff. We love our students.

Wishing you all a safe, healthy, and socially-distanced Spring Break. We will see you all when daily meal deliveries resume on Monday, April 13.

#GCSchools #WeCARE #TeamKentucky #TogetherKY #HealthyAtHome
